# Audience Guardrails

> **This is a bible file.** See `doc-governance.mdc` — it may not be edited without explicit user approval.

---

## The Two Audiences

### Primary audience: individuals

Patients, caregivers, and family members managing their own or a dependent's health.

The individual is **always** the end-user whose interests the product serves. Every product decision — features, language, defaults, data flows — must serve this person first.

### Additional audiences: clinicians, care teams, institutions, researchers — and businesses as distribution channels

Clinicians, care teams, institutions, and researchers may be **active workspace users** under the individual's explicit, scoped, revocable grant (or a care relationship / legal basis / research consent). Hospitals, clinics, and employers may additionally deploy WellBe as a **distribution channel**.

In every case the individual remains the **data controller**. Using a workspace or deploying the product never confers control over, or default access to, an individual's data. It brings WellBe to individuals. It does not direct what WellBe does for those individuals, and it does not own or access their data.

---

## What "Business as Distributor" Means — Precisely

| Role | Relationship to WellBe |
|---|---|
| Individual (patient/caregiver) | Primary user. Product serves this person. Data belongs to this person. |
| Business (hospital, employer, clinic) | Deployment channel. Licenses WellBe to reach individuals. No data access unless each individual explicitly grants it. |
| Clinician | Third party the individual may choose to share context with — via user-controlled share features. Never a primary user. |

A hospital deploying WellBe to its patients is using WellBe as a distribution channel. Each patient remains the user. The hospital does not gain access to patient data, cannot enable features on patients' behalf, and cannot aggregate patient data for its own purposes without each patient's explicit opt-in.

---

## Hard Prohibitions

These are never allowed in any WellBe feature description, spec text, system design doc, or safety doc:

1. **Every feature must benefit the individual.** A feature may serve a clinician, institution, or researcher, but it must also make sense from, and benefit, the individual user. A feature that delivers value only to a business/clinician and not the individual does not belong.

2. **No default or institution-controlled framing.** Language like "institution-managed", "hospital-controlled", or any capability an institution can switch on for users by default is prohibited. Clinician/institution/researcher workspaces are allowed, but always grant-gated and individual-controlled.

3. **No institutional data access by default.** No audience may access, aggregate, or share individual data without that individual's explicit, scoped grant — regardless of deployment relationship. Institutions receive only aggregate, consented, privacy-preserving intelligence.

4. **Clinician/institution/researcher may be active workspace users, never controllers.** They act only within the scope the individual granted; the individual always controls how the product behaves on their data and what is shared.

---

## What Is Allowed

- Features that work better when deployed via a business (e.g., a company health program deploys WellBe to employees) — **allowed**, as long as the employee (individual) is the user and controls their own data.
- B2B deployment language in business-context documents (sales materials, marketing, partnership agreements) — **allowed**. Not allowed in system design, feature specs, or safety docs.
- Features that let an individual share context with their care team — **allowed**. This is user-controlled sharing, not institutional access.
- Features that adapt to organizational context (e.g., different care pathways by geography or employer health plan) — **allowed**, as long as the individual's data control and product experience are not diminished.

---

## Privacy Rule (Applies in All Deployment Contexts)

Even in a B2B deployment:
- The individual's data belongs to the individual.
- The deploying business cannot read, aggregate, or export individual data without each person's explicit opt-in.
- Cross-patient or aggregate insights are never a business default. They are user-initiated features.
- If the individual leaves the business (e.g., changes employer), their data follows them — it does not remain with the business.

---

## Language Audit Checklist

Before any agent writes feature descriptions, spec text, or doc content, run this checklist:

- [ ] Does this feature also benefit the individual user (not only a clinician/institution)? → If not, it does not belong.
- [ ] Is every non-individual access grant-based, scoped, purpose-bound, and revocable (no default or institution-enabled access)? → If not, remove or reframe.
- [ ] Does it use "institution-managed", "hospital-controlled", or imply any access an institution can switch on by default? → Remove or reframe.
- [ ] For institution surfaces: is access aggregate-only and consented, with no default individual-level access? → If not, remove.
- [ ] Is the individual the controller making decisions about their own data and experience? → If not, the framing is wrong.
- [ ] Does the feature still make sense for a single individual with no organizational affiliation? → The personal core must always stand alone.

All five checks must pass before the content is written.

---

## Escalation

If a proposed feature fails the language audit checklist and cannot be reframed to serve the individual user — it is out of scope for WellBe. Surface this to the user: "This feature as described only serves [business/clinician/institution]. It does not appear to serve the individual user. It is out of scope unless the design is changed."

Do not add out-of-scope features to Jira or docs without explicit user decision.
